Indeed, in this scenario, it is necessary to 
                re-think the approach toward extremism and radicalisation. Such a rethinking must involve not just socio-technical systems (
                e.g. law enforcement agencies, social work, local bureaucracies and so forth) but also politics and ruling classes. In general, policy and politics towards extremism and radicalisation have been changed in recent years, after some spectacular and massive terrorist attacks occurred (
                Coolsaet, 2018; 
                Githens-Mazer, 2012; 
                Schmid, 2013). In addition, politics has delegated the task to contrast extremist to specific technical or bureaucratic agencies, depoliticising the problem. On the contrary, this open letter is based on three suggestions:
